## example-error-handling

# Error Handling Best Practices

## TRIGGER
When implementing functions that interact with external systems or handle user input.

## RULES

### Exception Handling
- Use try-catch blocks for operations that can fail
- Catch specific exceptions, not generic Exception
- Log errors with context for debugging
- Don't swallow exceptions silently

### User-Facing Errors
- Return user-friendly error messages
- Don't expose stack traces to users
- Provide actionable guidance when errors occur
- Use HTTP status codes correctly (400 for bad request, 500 for server error)

### Validation
- Validate input at API boundaries
- Return clear validation error messages
- Check for null/empty values before processing
- Use data annotations or FluentValidation

### Logging
- Log errors with sufficient context
- Include request IDs for tracing
- Don't log sensitive data (passwords, tokens)
- Use appropriate log levels (Error, Warning, Info)

### Recovery
- Implement retry logic for transient failures
- Provide fallback values when appropriate
- Clean up resources in finally blocks
- Use Circuit Breaker pattern for external calls


